 VPN or Peering (Private Connectivity)



 ðŸ”¹ What it is 

VPN or VPC/VNet Peering provides a secure, private connection between two networks.

ðŸ‘‰ It connects:

 Cloud â†” On-premise (VPN)
 Cloud â†” Cloud (Peering)

Traffic does NOT go over the public internet.



 ðŸ”¹ Types (Basic Understanding)

 1ï¸âƒ£ VPN (Hybrid Connectivity)

 Connects on-prem data center to cloud
 Encrypted tunnel over internet

Example:

```
Office Network â†” VPN â†” Cloud VPC
```



 2ï¸âƒ£ VPC / VNet Peering

 Connects two cloud networks privately
 No encryption needed (cloud internal)

Example:

```
VPC-A â†” Peering â†” VPC-B
```



 ðŸ”¹ Why It Is Needed

 1ï¸âƒ£ Hybrid Cloud

 Access on-prem servers from cloud
 Gradual migration to cloud

 2ï¸âƒ£ Security

 No public IP exposure
 Private IP communication only



 ðŸ”¹ Linux Admin Role 

 1ï¸âƒ£ Access on-prem servers

 SSH to on-prem servers using private IP
 Apps communicate securely across networks



 2ï¸âƒ£ Debug Routing Issues (Very Important)

If connectivity fails, Linux admin checks:

1ï¸âƒ£ Correct route exists

ip route


2ï¸âƒ£ Can reach remote network

ping
traceroute


3ï¸âƒ£ Firewall allows traffic

 Cloud SG / NSG
 On-prem firewall
 OS firewall

4ï¸âƒ£ No CIDR overlap

 Overlapping IP ranges break VPN/peering



 ðŸ”¹ Common Problems (Real World)

âŒ Cloud server cannot reach on-prem DB

Reasons:

 Missing route to on-prem CIDR
 Firewall blocking traffic
 Overlapping CIDR ranges



 ðŸ”¹ Traffic Flow (Easy to Teach)

Cloud VM (10.0.1.10)
      â†“
   VPN / Peering
      â†“
